The given expression can be rewritten using the Double Angle form, which can be defined as follows

\begin{align*}
2b^2 \sin C \cos C + 2bc \sin C \cos B = 42 * 2
\end{align*}

Using Double angle formulas, we can simplify this to

\begin{align*}
b^2 \sin 2C + bc \sin(C + B) = 42*2
\end{align*}

Using the fact that sum of all inner angles in a triangle equals 180 degree, we can say that \(C + B = 180 - A = A\). Hence the above equation simplifies to

\begin{align*}
b^2 \sin 2C + bc \sin(2A) = 42*2
\end{align*}

Substituting the area using Heron's formula,

\begin{align*}
b^2 \sin 2C + Area = 42*2
\end{align*}

Rearranging, we find that

\begin{align*}
Area = 42*2 - b^2 \sin 2C
\end{align*}

Therefore, the area of triangle ABC is \boxed{84 - b^2 \sin 2C}.
